Members of the Assembly of Wales do not want to “like muppets”
Among some members of the National Assembly there is dissatisfaction with the proposal to accept the acronym MWP for their name (from Member of the Welsh Parliament – Member of Parliament of Wales).
A problematic solution is the plans to change the name of the Assembly to Parliament of Wales.
Members of the Assembly from various political parties are concerned about possible jokes with this acronym.
A Labour member, expressing his party's opinion, expressed concern that the new acronym " rhymes Twp and Pwp".
For our readers, not from Wales: in Welsh twp means "tupica", and pwp means "cushka".
According to a member of the Assembly from the Wales Party, his organization as a whole was "dissatisfied" and offered other options.
Conservative party representatives "do not object" to the new acronym, but note that MWP is close to writing to the word Muppet (mappet).
In this context, the letter w in Welsh is pronounced roughly as the letter u in the Yorkshire dialect of English.
The Assembly Committee, currently drafting a change of name law, made the following statement: “The final decision on how the members of the Assembly will be named will, of course, remain with them”.
The Wales Administration Act 2017 authorizes the National Assembly of Wales to change its name.
In June, the Committee published a public opinion poll on the proposed options, according to which the “Parliament of Wales” option, instead of “Assembly”, had found broad support among the local population.
With regard to the name of the members of the Assembly, the Committee preferred the option “Members of Parliament of Wales” (Welsh Parliament Members, or WMP), while the MWP option received the greatest public support.
It seems that members of the Assembly are offering other options, but it will be difficult for the presiding member, Elin Jones, to find a satisfactory solution, recalling that the draft law on change should be submitted in a few weeks.
Reform laws would include other modifications to the Assembly ' s work process, including new rules on disqualification of Assembly members and the structure of the Committee system.
Members of the Assembly will vote in favour of the final version of their name during the debate on the bill.
