John Edward: Knowledge of languages is of great importance to the citizens of the world
Scottish independent schools continue the tradition of brilliant education, which was reaffirmed in 2018: outstanding examination results have demonstrated individual and collective success in sports, art, music, and other socially important disciplines.
These schools are part of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), with more than 30,000 students all over Scotland, and aim to provide the highest level of services for pupils and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further higher education, their career choices, and the status of citizens of the world.
As part of the education sector, which is responsible for designing and implementing an individual school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, you call to his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, you turn to his heart."
This is a strong indication that we cannot rely solely on English if we are to build relationships with and trust citizens of other countries.
From this year ' s latest examinations, we see languages taking the lead in league tables and having the highest score in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of pupils who studied foreign languages received the highest "A" rating.
Data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 per cent of students received "A" in Mandarin (Normary Chinese), while 72 per cent of those studying German, 69 per cent of those studying French and 63 per cent of those studying Spanish also received "A".
This proves that in independent schools in Scotland, foreign languages are clearly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
Language subjects are now in the same demand as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other educational institutions.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that, among the reasons that made it difficult for employers to fill vacancies, 17 per cent was due to language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly the key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising jobs require language skills, these skills are needed in a globalized world.
No matter what profession the student chooses, if he learns a second language, in the future he will receive a real advantage by learning another additional skill that will be useful for him throughout his life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows more than one foreign language a competitive advantage.
According to a YouTube survey in which more than 4,000 adult British participated in 2013, 75 per cent were unable to speak well enough in foreign language to support the conversation, and French proved to be the only two-digit language spoken by 15 per cent of respondents.
That is why investing in language education is so relevant now.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
Scotland's schools have quite a variety of languages that are taught — each school has its own set of languages.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered most important to Britain in the light of the country's future development until 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests may be, independent schools will always have a choice of several languages with teaching staff whose members are specialists in these languages.
Scottish independent schools seek to create an environment of learning that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary to achieve success, regardless of the future they face.
At present, it cannot be denied that, in the global business environment, languages continue to be vital to the future development of the country, so that this should be appropriately reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages need to be seen as “skills of international communication”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, which provides diversity and benefits for Scottish youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edwards, Director, Board of Independent Schools of Scotland
