The course, first offered to students this year, tells how a healthy sleep habit contributes to academic and sports performance, as well as how it improves the overall well-being of the individual.
Paul Barreira, a Harvard Medical School psychiatry professor and executive director of the University's Health Service, said that the university decided to introduce the course after it was revealed that students were severely sleepy during the school week.
The class lasts one hour and students perform a number of interactive assignments.
One section of the class offers an image of a room in a dormitory, where students, by clicking on coffee cups, curtains, simulators and books, learn how each of these actions and substances — coffee, the light that causes sleep deprivation — affects sports outcomes, and how important it is to get enough sleep every day.
In another section, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
An interactive campus map encourages participants to reflect on their daily lives.
"We understand that these classes will not change students' behavior at once.
But we believe they have a right to know, like any other person has a right to know, for example, how smoking affects his health," added Professor Chaisler.
According to him, a false sense of pride for being able to "plow all night" is still quite common, and modern technologies, just as increasing pressure on students means sleep deprivation is becoming a problem.
He said that enough sleep of good quality was a student's “secret weapon” to deal with stress, nervous exhaustion and anxiety, and even to deal with overweight, as lack of sleep puts the brain in a state of starvation, making it constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californiaman studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaisler develop the course by attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
