World Wide Web inventor plans to launch a new Internet for Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, launches a startup that claims to compete with Facebook, Amazon, and Google.
The latest technological legend project, Inrupt, is a company based on the open Berners-Lee Solid platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people to give access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with the Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the goal of Inrupt was to gain "world domination".
"We have to do it now," he says about his startup.
"This is a historic moment".
The application uses Solid technology that allows people to create their own "personal online data repositories" or POD.
It can contain contact lists, file lists, a calendar, a music library and other personal and professional data tools.
The application operates on the same principle as Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify -- everything can be used in the same browser and at the same time.
The uniqueness of a personal online data warehouse is that it is fully managed by the user, who can access any necessary information.
The company calls this principle "personal empowerment through data".
According to John Bruce's CEO, Inrupt's idea is that the company has provided resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to all.
The company currently consists of Berners Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several regular developers contracted to work on the project, and a volunteer programmer community.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team were not negotiating with Facebook and Google on whether his companies should make fundamental changes that would completely change all their business models overnight.
"We don't ask their permissions".
In his post on Medium, published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt mission is to provide commercial energy and ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of a new network built on Solid".
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating a World Wide Web consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee's voice has been quite influential in the debate about neutrality on the network.
Even starting Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Internet Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am incredibly optimistic about this next era of the Internet," Berners-Lee says.
