National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
A new study conducted in one of the Scotland Highlands is designed to show how bats use the landscape in search of food.
It is hoped that the data obtained will provide a new perspective on the behaviour of unique winged mammals and will assist in the continued conservation of the species.
A study organized by National Foundation scientists in Scotland will examine common non-tops, non-topsoprano, and brown long hair bats and Dobanton nightstands inhabiting Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be installed at some points around the site to monitor bat action throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile site surveys using manual detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all records will determine the frequency of screams as well as the activities for which the different groups of these animals are responsible.
A habitat map will then be drawn up and a report prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour on the scale of the landscape.
Rob Dewar, the NTS conservation advisor, hopes that these results will show which habitats are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the main areas of habitat management, such as grassland formation, as well as ways to maintain forest areas optimal for bats and other related species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and throughout the UK have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened with extinction due to construction and development work that affects their habitat and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can be dangerous, as well as adhesive tape for flies, chemical processing of building materials, and hunting of pet cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, their night hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echo-location techniques to accurately identify the obstacles to flight.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the issue of bat populations very seriously.
The organization has 10 trained experts who conduct regular interviews, on-site checks and sometimes rescue.
The organization even created the first and only bat reservation in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten species of Scottish bats live.
Real estate manager David Thompson says the property is the perfect territory for them.
"Here, in Threave, a great place for bats," he says.
"Here are old buildings, many old trees and all elements of good habitat.
But much about bats remains unknown, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us to better understand what they need for a prosperous existence."
It recalls the importance of testing for bats prior to maintenance within private domain, as the inadvertent destruction of one nest can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young people, and possibly even to the destruction of the entire local population.
The bats are protected by law, their destruction, harassment or destruction of their habitats is illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish bat conservation fund officer, appeals to the public for help.
She says, "We have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don't know how many of their individual species live."
