How a Trade War with America Can Be Good for Beijing
Experts believe that the first rounds of the US-China trade war were deafening, and while the battle is far from over, the divisions between countries can benefit Beijing in the long run.
Donald Trump, the President of the United States, made the first warning earlier this year, taxing major Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel, and aluminium.
The largest escalation occurred this week, when new tariffs affected products worth $200 billion (150 billion pounds), effectively taxing half of all goods coming from China to the United States.
Beijing has dealt equivalent counter-attacks each time, recently imposing $60 billion worth of duties on US goods of between 5 and 10 per cent.
China has promised that the response against the US will be equivalent every time, and the world’s second largest economy is unlikely to begin to experience at least the slightest difficulty in the near future.
Making Washington retreat means giving in to demands, but publicly giving in to the US would be too shameful for Xi Jinping, China’s president.
However, experts believe that if Beijing can play its cards correctly, the US trade war pressure can provide long-term support to China, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that an early political decision in Washington or Beijing can create conditions that will lead to economic stump in any of these countries is in fact far more dangerous than previously acknowledged by observers," says Abigail Grace, a researcher at the Center for New American Security, specializing in Asia.
